            .</p>
               <p>WILLIAM LEWIS THORNBORROW. I <rs id="t18300916-340-viclabel1752" type="occupation">have a small independence</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18300916-340-victim2772 t18300916-340-viclabel1752"></join>, and went to receive it on Wednesday, the 16th of September - I met the prisoner, whom I knew; I asked how he fared - he said but badly; I proposed to give him a good dinner and a shilling, which I did, and left four sovereigns in possession of the landlady; on the Thursday morning he called on me again, and asked if he could do me any little service - I said Yes, he might brush my clothes and clean my shoes; he took the papers out of my pocket, and found the note of the four sovereigns, which I had left with Mrs. Crouch - he took it, and got the balance; I had drawn 3s. 6d. the night before.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18300916-340-person2773">
                  ANN 
                  CROUCH
               <interp inst="t18300916-340-person2773" type="surname" value="CROUCH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300916-340-person2773" type="given" value="ANN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300916-340-person2773" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . The last witness left me four sovereigns and a friend of mine wrote this paper; I gave it to the prosecutor - the prisoner brought it next morning, and said he came for the money, which I gave him; there were three sovereigns and 16s. 6d. - he had had 3s. 6d. of me the night before.</p>
               <p>Prisoner. He got drunk the day before, and I took him from this lady's house - he would have a cab, and sent me back for 3s. 6d. to pay for it; he then sent me back for 1l., but I could not get that - he told me to call on him the next morning, which I did; he got out of bed, and told me to sit down - he sent for some gin, and we had four half-pints one after the other; he had promised me some time before, that when he got this money he would assist me - I asked him then to do it; he gave me this paper, and told me to go and get it, and to pay him so much a week.</p>

               <p>W. L. THORNBORROW. There is not a word of truth in it - I had not seen him for nine months before; I wrote a petition for him to get re-established in the Police, where he had been before, but lost his situation; he showed me some names of characters - he had an unfavourable answer sent back; I was perfectly sober.</p>
               <p>ANN CROUCH re-examined. Q. Did the prisoner come back for 3s. 6d. the same night? A. Yes; he returned in ten minutes, said the man must have a cab, and requested me to let him have 3s. 6d., which I did - he wanted a sovereign, but I would not let him have that.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18300916-340-verdict1753" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18300916-340-verdict1753" type="verdictCategory" value="notGuilty"></interp>
               NOT GUILTY
            </rs>.</p>
